Exploring the Data

  • We will only be looking at the first week of data
  • Observed relationships between variables
  • Motivation for transformations
  • Initial basic linear models
  • Exploring interactions

Our Approach to the Data

  • Logarithmic transformation of the data to account for right skew

Variable Relationships

  • X lables have been added to correlations with p values \(\geq\) 0.01
  • What are the relationships between the variables we have been given?

Exploratory Analysis

  • A look at our initial linear regression model
  • Dwell is affected differently depending on the form of payment

Interactions

  • What happens to cash when lift is cycled vs when it isnt?
  • We included interaction terms to help account for these differences

Random Effects

  • There are still some elements to our model that are still not accounted for in a basic linear model
  • What possible groups are we missing?

Group Differences: line_id & site_id

  • Site_id and line_id have particularly drastic differences in terms of mean dwell time
  • Site_id has a strong relationship with time and the pay-leave pay class

Spatial Relationships

  • The stops with the highest mean dwell time appear randomly distributed
  • More customers pay using Go-To cards on the outside the city centers

Model Limitations

  • There are clear disagreements between the models
  • In particular, pay class and interactions with the variable
    • We are hesitent to fit our model on the combined data

Data Constraints

  • Limited time frame (only 2 weeks of data)
  • What other trends might we see with more data?

Weather Constraints

  • The only data we added was weather, which was fairly similar across the two weeks
    • We may want to consider other variables in the future

Conclusion

  • Our model is an inferential model, not a predictive model
  • We hope to illustrate that certain variables and the interaction
    between them lead to quite different effects on mean dwell time
  • With the input of more data, Metro Transits team would be able to
    develop a model capable of prediction
